Park said stricter border warnings between North Korea and China and higher charges levied by smugglers with people were key elements.
Pyongyang has not issued any official statement.
The vast majority of those fleeing North Korea are being offered South Korean citizenship rights.
Seoul says more than 30,000 North Koreans have crossed the border illegally since the end of the Korean War in 1953.
Most are fleeing to China, but it has the longest border with North Korea, and it is easier to cross them than the well-to-do zone between North and South Korea.
China views the refugees as illegal immigrants rather than refugees and often forces them to return to their home countries.
Relations between North and South Korea, which are still at war, have technically improved considerably in the past month.
Earlier this month, the leaders of the two countries met in Pyongyang for talks that focused mainly on adjournment negotiations on nuclear disarmament.
This was after a historic meeting in June between US President Donald Trump and Kim Jong-un in Singapore, where they agreed in earnest to work together towards a nuclear-free Korean Peninsula.
On Saturday, Ri Yong Ho, North Korea’s foreign minister, however, lectured U.S. businessmen about the lack of progress since then.
“Without trust in the United States, there is no certainty about the security of our country and under such circumstances it is impossible for us to unilaterally take down our nuclear weapons first,” Ri said in a speech at the U.N. General Assembly in New York.
