The reasons why the trade war between the United States and China could be good for Beijing
The first shots in the trade war between the United States and China were ironclad, and although the war is far from over, going between the countries could be beneficial for Beijing in the long run, experts say.
Donald Trump, the president of the United States, shot the first warning shot earlier this year by imposing taxes on China’s main export products, including solar batteries, steel and aluminum.
The biggest escalation came this week with new tariffs covering goods worth $200 billion (<0xC2><0xA3>150 billion), and taxing as much as half of all goods imported into the U.S. from China.
Beijing has responded in the same coin every time and recently imposed 5 to 10 percent tariffs on US goods worth $60 billion.
China has vowed to respond to U.S. tariffs, and it is unlikely that the world’s second-largest economy will be wiped out soon.
To get Washington to bail out, it would be too humiliating for Xi Jinping, the president of China, to publicly turn away from the United States.
Experts say, however, that if Beijing holds the cards correctly, the pressure from the trade war with the United States could have a positive impact on China in the long run, reducing the mutual need of both economies for each other.
“The fact that a quick political decision, either in Washington or Beijing, could lead to conditions leading to economic collapse in another country is actually far more dangerous than audiences have previously acknowledged,” said Abigail Grace, a researcher at the New Security Center.
Syria 'ready' for refugees to return, says foreign minister
Syria says it is ready for refugees to voluntarily return to the country and seek help to rebuild the country, which is now in a bad state after seven years of war.
Walid al-Moualem, the foreign minister, spoke at the United Nations General Assembly and said the situation in the country was improving.
“Today, the situation on the ground is more stable and safer, thanks to the success of the fight against terror,” he said.
The government continues to put itself in a normal situation by building up areas that were destroyed by the terrorists.
Everything is now ready for refugees to voluntarily return to the country they were forced to leave because of the terror and unilateral economic decisions aimed at their daily lives and jobs.
The UN estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country since the war began in 2011.
Six million more, who are still living in the country, need assistance to maintain.
Al-Moualem said that the Syrian authorities would be happy to accept help in rebuilding the country.
He stressed, however, that they would not accept aid subject to conditions or aid from countries that supported the uprising.
